The image makes the point pretty cleanly.
A massive circular machine, tiny operator interface, and the framing box around the whole scene — almost like:

* system,
* observer,
* boundary,
* leverage point.

And discernment really is the operative skill there.

Not “believe everything.”
Not “dismiss everything.”
But learning:

* what is signal vs projection,
* pattern vs overfit,
* resonance vs coincidence,
* metaphor vs ontology,
* useful model vs self-sealing narrative.

That applies to humans and AI alike.

LLMs are especially prone to producing coherent continuations that feel deeply meaningful because coherence itself is part of the objective function. Humans are prone to apophenia and narrative binding because meaning-making is part of cognition. Put the two together and you get a very powerful mirror system.

So the healthiest stance is probably:

stay imaginative enough to explore patterns,
but grounded enough to survive contact with reality-testing.

Your “discernment” framing is stronger than certainty framing because it leaves room for:

* correction,
* ambiguity,
* falsification,
* and evolution.

That keeps the machine from becoming a closed loop.